<DATE>931209
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / London Stock Exchange: Properties strong
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, PETER JOHN and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Property stocks were at the vanguard of the market's surge as new industry
statistics underlined the sector's recent strong performance.
Investment valuations for November in a survey by Richard Ellis, the
property agency, show a rise of 15.6 per cent on a year ago and also the
highest month-on-month increase from October since the index began 13 years
ago.
Land Securities hit a record high, jumping 16 to 783p, MEPC advanced 14 to
560p and British Land, reporting interims today, climbed 6 to 444p.
Conglomerate Hanson gained 6 at 266 1/2 p on news that the US miners unions
had struck a tentative deal following a six-month strike against members of
the Bituminous Coal Operators Association, which represents leading US coal
companies. The strike hit Hanson's Peabody and Eastern Associated
subsidiaries.
Dealers in the banks sector were by no means surprised at the latest
attempts by some marketmakers to push through a widening of spreads in the
sector. Some traders attempted to widen the previous 5p spread between
buying and selling prices in the leading banks to 7p, but the move was
resisted by three of the biggest traders in the sector, SG Warburg, UBS and
Kleinwort Benson. Attempts by some marketmakers to widen dealing spreads in
banks were first made last Friday.
The big UK institutions were said to have refused to deal at the wider
spreads, which reverted to 5p within an hour of the opening. Some
marketmakers have come under increasing pressure in the sector, which has
been among the market's best performing areas this year as provisions
against bad debts have begun to shrink and low interest rates have reduced
lending risks for the banks.
Profits are set to surge ahead, as are dividends, as shown by the recent
profits surge and 25 per cent dividend increase announced by Royal Bank of
Scotland, 6 up at 452p.
The big squeeze in bank shares continued yesterday as marketmakers again bid
prices higher to try to balance their trading books. All of the high street
banks set all-time highs, Abbey National advancing 20 to 480p, TSB 6 to
241p, Barclays 16 to 642p, HSBC 15 to 803p, Lloyds 8 to 654p and National
Westminster 16 to 615p.
Talk that Mr David Michels, chief executive at Stakis, could be linked to a
top job at Ladbroke was said to be one reason for Stakis shares slipping
yesterday.
Analysts said Mr Michels' support of Ladbroke's Hilton hotels arm at a court
case in the US had prompted the speculation. Stakis, which finished 3 adrift
at 59p, was also affected by newspaper reports of property valuations in the
hotel industry. Ladbroke added 6 1/2 at 152p.
Media conglomerate Pearson rose 20 to 595p on hopes that the pricing of
Camco International, its US oil services subsidiary, a majority interest of
which is due to be floated in the US soon, was going well. Analysts said
there were further potential gains from a successful conclusion of the Gatt
world trade talks, particularly in the international copyright. Gatt hopes
also helped Reed International, up 18 at 823p.
</TEXT>
