<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / World Stock Markets (America): New Dow high on selective
late demand
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks finished on a mixed note yesterday, but blue chip issues followed
Tuesday's record-setting performance with an impressive encore, writes Frank
McGurty in New York.
By the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was 15.65 stronger at
3,734.53, beating the short-lived high of 3,718.88. But the more broadly
based Stan-dard &amp; Poor's 500 slipped 0.47 to 466.29. The American SE
composite was up 1.47 at 468.87 but the Nasdaq composite lost 1.46 at
767.89. NYSE volume was heavy at 314.4m shares.
Equities limped through the morning with little sense of direction ahead of
today's producer price data. Tuesday's record closing high could not dispel
the flat mood, nor could the stagnant US Treasury market, where bonds across
the maturity range trod water in relaxed anticipation of Thursday's
inflation data. In late trading the benchmark 30-year issue was barely
higher at 101 5/32 , amid expectations of a modest 0.2 per cent increase in
last month's wholesale prices.
The day's only new economic data, the Federal Reserve's Beige Book summary
of regional conditions, only served to reinforce the impression of strong
growth and low inflation suggested by last week's stream of statistics.
The Dow briefly touched negative territory in the early afternoon, before
spurting ahead in a late burst of buying in a handful of pivotal stocks.
Among the contributing issues, JP Morgan, the US securities house, added
Dollars 1 1/2 at Dollars 72 3/4 after raising its dividend. Eastman Kodak
was up Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 62 1/2 and Aluminum Co of America gained
Dollars 3 1/4 at Dollars 72 1/2 .
Airlines were again among the most active stocks. Continental's 'B' stock
was marked down Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 20 1/2 after an offering of 7m new
shares at Dollars 20 each.
UAL, the parent of United Airlines, edged ahead Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 150
5/8 on reports of progress in negotiations over a move by its unions to
acquire 60 per cent of the company.
With Comex gold prices on the rise, mining issues were in play. Placer Dome
rose Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 24 1/2 , while American Barrick climbed
Dollars 1 to Dollars 28 1/8 . On the Amex, Pegasus Gold advanced Dollars 1
3/4 to Dollars 22 1/2 and Echo Bay Mines was Dollars  7/8 ahead at Dollars
13 5/8 .
An announcement by Xerox that it would cut about 10 per cent of its
97,500-strong workforce sent the stock Dollars 5 1/4 higher to Dollars 86.
Marriott International added Dollars 2 at Dollars 27 after Wertheim Schroder
upgraded its rating from 'neutral' to 'buy'.
Canada
Toronto finished at a record peak in active trading, boosted by strong gains
among gold and other mining stocks.
The TSE 300 index climbed 42.2 to 4,307.7. Rises led falls by 492 to 336
after volume of 79.1m shares. The golds index jumped 4.9 per cent as the
spot gold price rose USDollars 6.20 an ounce in New York.
</TEXT>
