<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / International Company News: Litton subsidiary buys back own
shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Litton Industries' oil services subsidiary is to pay Dollars 558m to buy
back a block of its own shares as part of a series of measures to shape it
as a free-standing company.
Litton said its Western Atlas subsidiary will pay Dollars 358m in cash and
Dollars 200m in seven-year notes to buy the 29.5 per cent of the
subsidiary's shares held by Dresser, another oil services company.
Western Atlas, which derives 60 per cent of its annual Dollars 2bn sales
from oil services and the rest from industrial automation, is expected to be
spun off before the end of the year. Litton shareholders will receive one
share in the new company for each Litton share they own.
Litton also said it would take an after-tax charge of Dollars 172m in the
current quarter to reflect the accelerated depreciation of some of Western
Atlas' assets. The subsidiary specialises in the use of information
technology in exploration and drilling operations and demand for the newest
technology had been stronger than expected, forcing the accelerated
write-downs of older equipment.
Mr Alton Brann, president and chief executive, said the purchase from
Dresser would allow both Litton and Dresser to concentrate their investments
on their core businesses.
Mr John Murphy, chairman and chief executive of Dresser, said the deal would
give his company 'greater liquidity and flexibility'. Dresser, which said it
would record a Dollars 150m after-tax profit on the sale, is in the process
of completing an all-share takeover of another oil services company, Baroid,
in a deal currently valued at Dollars 750m.
</TEXT>
