<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / International Company News: S&amp;P wins right to retain notes
on Pan Am
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A US judge ruled yesterday that Standard &amp; Poor's, the ratings agency, would
not have to turn over to creditors of Pan Am, the defunct US airline,
information the agency had gathered about a bid in 1992 to fund a
reorganisation of Pan Am by rival carrier Delta Air Lines.
Lawyers representing Pan Am's creditors had issued a subpoena to Standard &amp;
Poor's demanding it hand over the information, which they said was needed
for a lawsuit Pan Am had filed against Delta for withdrawing from the
reorganisation plan.
Standard &amp; Poor's compiled the information on Delta from meetings,
correspondence and other communications with the airline, and had intended
to use it to evaluate how Delta would be affected by its funding of a
planned reorganisation of Pan Am.
Yesterday's decision overturns an earlier ruling by a bankruptcy court that
had compelled Standard &amp; Poor's to give the information to lawyers of Pan
Am's creditors. That decision was made on the grounds that the ratings
agency was not a news organisation gathering the information for purposes of
journalism, and therefore not protected by the right to free speech
guaranteed in the US constitution.
However, district court judge Ms Loretta Preska of Manhattan ruled that
Standard &amp; Poor's was entitled to the constitutional protections enjoyed by
news organisations.
</TEXT>
