<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / International Company News: YPF plans Dollars 1.25bn
investment programme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BARHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUENOS AIRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
YPF, Argentina's privatised oil company, plans to invest Dollars 1.25bn next
year to increase output, modernise production capacity and upgrade its
retail network.
It announced an Dollars 850m bond programme, the largest of its kind by an
Argentine company.
The company plans to invest Dollars 650m to increase production by 20 per
cent in 1994. Output is 380,000 b/d, and YPF aims to produce 450,000 b/d by
1995. It said much of the increased production would be exported to Chile
through a trans-Andean pipeline to be inaugurated next year.
Mr Jose Estenssoro, YPF president, said the company would invest Dollars
300m in exploration to lift reserves. A further Dollars 100m would be used
to upgrade operations to meet tougher environmental standards as part of a
Dollars 500m five-year plan.
The remaining Dollars 200m would be used to expand and modernise refinery
capacity and retail network.
YPF was partially privatised in June when the government sold 45 per cent of
the company for Dollars 3.04bn.
The investment programme is to be financed from cashflow and debt. In the
nine months to September, YPF reported net income of Dollars 394m, against
Dollars 145m in the same period of 1992.
Mr Cedric Bridger, vice-president, said YPF would launch Dollars 850m-worth
of bonds, to be spearheaded early next year by a Dollars 350m fixed rate,
10-year Yankee bond programme. Mr Bridger said the Yankee bonds, to be
placed by CS First Boston, would be used to retire Dollars 200m-worth of
costly local and World Bank debt and replenish working capital.
He said pricing would be decided after the government had placed Dollars
750m-worth of Global bonds today. YPF hopes to achieve similar or better
terms for its bonds.
The Yankee bonds will be followed by a Dollars 500m medium-term global note
programme.
</TEXT>
