<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / International Company News: Matsushita Electric to move
6,000 staff in restructuring
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Matsushita Electric yesterday announced a big restructuring in which it
plans to transfer 6,000 employees from administrative jobs to those directly
related to production, sales and new business development.
Matsushita said 30 per cent of its administrative workforce, or about 20,000
employees, would be transferred out of their current jobs during the next
three years. They will go to sales and new business development.
At a year-end gathering with the press yesterday, Mr Yoichi Morishita,
president, said the restructuring was essential to revitalise the company in
the face of a severe economic climate.
Under the restructuring, to be implemented in February, the functions and
structure of the company's headquarters in Osaka will also be revamped.
Development divisions will be restructured to find and develop new
technologies more efficiently.
The move by the world's largest consumer electronics group is aimed at
trimming its administrative operations and using its workforce more
effectively.
It comes as the consumer electronics industry faces one of the worst
downturns in its history, compounded by growing pressures to move a larger
part of manufacturing overseas to cope with the sharp rise of the yen.
Matsushita's restructuring plan also highlights the difficulty the group is
having in coming up with innovative products to stimulate sluggish consumer
demand.
While a large number of Japanese companies are struggling to adapt their
corporate structures to a tougher new era, Matsushita, in particular, has
been widely criticised for being bloated and bureaucratic. The company
employs 90,000 people in Japan and 250,000 worldwide.
Earlier this year, Mr Akio Tanii suddenly resigned as president following a
financial scandal. The event was seen by many in the industry as stemming
from Matsushita's excessively large and complex organisational structure.
Profits have also been poor. In the year ended March, Matsushita reported a
54 per cent decline in pre-tax profits, to Y168.4bn (Dollars 1.6bn), the
second year of a sharp decline.
Following a cool summer, which hit sales of air conditioning equipment, the
economy has remained flat.
</TEXT>
