<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / International Company News: Consortium buys E German coal
mine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Eastern Germany's highly-regulated utilities industry is set to be prised
open after an Anglo-American consortium yesterday completed the purchase of
one of the region's largest brown coal mines.
PowerGen of the UK, and NRG and Morrison-Knudsen of the US yesterday
acquired Mitteldeutsche Braunkohlenwerke (Mibrag) from the Treuhand
privatisation agency.
The consortium will invest more than DM1.3bn (Dollars 765m) between now and
the year 2004. It has agreed to guarantee 2,100 jobs until the end of the
decade in the three mines, two briquette plants, and a small generating
plant which it has acquired. The remainder of the Mibrag complex, employing
about 3,600, will be hived off from the consortium and placed under a
separate company.
Before German unification, Mibrag, which straddles the eastern states of
Saxony-Anhalt and Saxony, employed more than 55,000 people.
The consortium will target the investments primarily on modernising the
mines and introducing the environmental technology required to reduce
sharply the sulphuric oxide content of brown coal, a soft coal widely used
in energy-production in eastern Germany.
Mr David Petersen, president of NRG, said Mibrag would produce about about
20m tonnes a year.
Although energy consumption had fallen sharply in eastern Germany because of
the decline of the region's manufacturing base and growing competition from
the gas sector, the consortium has secured coal delivery contracts. Mr
Petersen said these would guarantee the economic viability of Mibrag.
Mibrag's coal will be delivered locally to the 1,600-MW power plant at
Lippendorf, owned by Veag, eastern Germany's main utility company; to Meag,
a regional utility group; and to Schkopau, an 800-MW power plant. Schkopau
is being built by VKR, the electricity arm of PreussenElektra, the large
German utility company.
The consortium has managed to secure a 44 per cent stake in Schkopau and
will sign the agreement tomorrow. Mr Petersen said the consortium's
acquisition of Mibrag and Schkopau was a 'milestone in the participation in
the German energy industry. This will mean a more open and competitive
industry.'
</TEXT>
