<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / UK Company News: Allders meets flotation forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Allders, the department store and tax and duty-free retailer, has fulfilled
the forecasts made in its flotation prospectus.
The group, which went public last month, made a pro-forma pre-tax profit of
Pounds 13.3m in the year to September 30, compared to its forecast of Pounds
13.2m.
The shares closed yesterday at 191p, down 1p on the day but ahead of the
170p flotation price.
Lord Prior, chairman, said consumer confidence was still fragile. However,
he was confident the current year would see the benefit of new stores opened
in 1992 and 1993, and new tax and duty free outlets. He said 'with our
financial position now established, we are well placed to secure future
growth'.
Allders learnt last Friday that the Canadian government was cancelling the
redevelopment and privatisation of Toronto airport, which would have given
Allders the right to operate shops in terminals 1 and 2. Allders is hoping
for compensation for the preparation work it has done.
Actual pre-tax profit was Pounds 6.36m (loss Pounds 3.44m), after an
interest charge of Pounds 8.85m (Pounds 10.6m), which would have been Pounds
7m lower had the group had the Pounds 75m cash raised through the flotation
at the start of the year. The group had been heavily borrowed because of its
management buy-out in 1989.
Group sales rose 16.4 per cent to Pounds 685.5m and operating profits were
Pounds 23.1m (Pounds 15.2m), including associates of Pounds 3.26m (Pounds
2.24m) and before exceptional costs of Pounds 7.99m (Pounds 8.08m) which
related to rent on an unused property.
Pro-forma fully diluted earnings per share were 13.9p, against an estimate
of 13.7p. The group said at the time of the float that it would not pay a
dividend in respect of 1992-93, but if it had been quoted throughout the
year would have paid a total of 6.1p.
Department store sales were up 10.6 per cent to Pounds 286.6m, with the
increase due to new stores. Operating profits in this division rose 21 per
cent to Pounds 12m, but this included a Pounds 1.2m benefit from a 53rd
trading week. The duty free shopping division increased sales 21 per cent to
Pounds 398.9m. Operating profits nearly doubled to Pounds 13.1m (Pounds
6.7m).
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Allders.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
