<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / UK Company News: Hopes launched of uplift in tanker shipping
 -Events which point to the end of a 20-year bear market in new shipbuilding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Attracting new money into tanker shipping has been a difficult task in
recent years. The banks had their fingers badly burned, while equity finance
has been hard to come by.
But there are signs of a change. The past six months have seen a rash of
equity issues which some analysts believe may herald the first significant
uplift in the tanker and bulk shipping market for two decades.
More than Dollars 500m (Pounds 335m) of new equity has been raised by means
of rights issues and share placings to finance spending on new and
second-hand vessels.
'We are seeing the end of a 20-year bear market in new shipbuilding,'
predicts Mr Mark McVicar, shipping analyst at NatWest Securities.
At the same time, family-owned shipping companies are taking the opportunity
to restructure their businesses to make them more transparent, and hence
more attractive to the institutional investor.
Recent equity issues have included:
Bona Shipholding. Established as a private company last year to own and
operate the tanker and product fleet of Leif Hoegh, a Norwegian shipping
group, Bona is raising Dollars 120m and seeking an Oslo listing. Its shares
will also be traded in London and the US after the offer closes on December
16. The effect will be to reduce Leif Hoegh's stake from 76 to about 42 per
cent. London &amp; Overseas Freighters. Lofs, a London-listed company controlled
by the Kulukundis family, has placed Dollars 75m of new shares and obtained
a listing on the US Nasdaq market. This reduces the Kulukundis holding from
85 to 24 per cent and gives the company greater exposure to US investors.
First Olsen Tankers. This company was set up to take over most of the
midsize - 100,000 to 150,000 dwt - tanker interests of the Norwegian
shipping group Fred Olsen &amp; Co. It completed a Dollars 105m share offering
last month. The deal left Fred Olsen and associates with an unchanged 45 per
cent of the shares, but brought in new institutional shareholders and
created a more tax-efficient structure.
Other recent developments have included the listing in Oslo last June of
Smedvig Tankships via a Dollars 138m offering, a Dollars 53m share issue by
Benor Tankers, a Bermuda-registered operator of product carriers and a
Dollars 61m rights issue by the Swedish ICB Shipping.
The amounts of equity being raised are tiny compared with the billions which
will be needed to renew the world tanker fleet over the next few years.
Together they would buy just five new supertankers. But they are seen by
shipping analysts as a hopeful sign of revival in the tanker sector.
Underlying this flurry of stock market activity is the expectation of a rise
in the charter rates for tankers and bulk carriers. Rates for a reasonably
modern super-tanker are about Dollars 14,000 a day. Some analysts hope for
an improvement in rates in the new year. On this will depend whether there
are any more equity issues.
Expectations of an upturn in rates are based on forecasts of economic
recovery and an upturn in demand for oil. They also hinge on the end of the
chronic overcapacity in tankers, which has depressed earnings for the past
two decades.
This overcapacity dates from the early 1970s, when new tankers were leaving
the shipyards in record numbers. New tanker construction doubled in 1973 and
again in 1974 before peaking at more than 35m dwt in 1975, just when the oil
crisis cut off demand for capacity.
Except for a short upward blip in market rates before the US-led attack on
Iraq during the Gulf war, when large amounts of oil were pumped out of the
Gulf and stored in tankers, the market has been dogged by excess capacity.
But many of these tankers built in the early 1970s are approaching their
fourth five-year survey, which can be a costly event. 'After 20 years you
have to replace a lot of steel,' says Mr Matthew Stainer, shipping analyst
at Schroder Securities.
'Charter rates have been so low that a lot of tonnage has not been well
maintained. Over the next five years half of the tanker fleet will move past
its 20th birthday.'
This ageing of the fleet has coincided with the introduction of tough
environmental controls by the US government and the International Maritime
Organisation. The US regulations will force shipowners to modernise their
fleets or face the prospect of being barred from American waters.
The main threat hanging over shipowners is the US Oil Pollution Act of 1990,
introduced in the wake of the Exxon Valdez disaster off the coast of Alaska,
and other recent oil spills. Some provisions of the act will not work
through until well into the next century, but others, such as the
requirement for new tankers to have double hulls, have taken immediate
effect.
The tough liability imposed on shipowners by the OPA has persuaded some
tanker operators to restructure their shipping holdings, reducing their
direct stakes. The aim is to ensure that liability for a spill stops with
the tanker subsidiary and cannot be enforced on the parent company. 'They
want to reduce their catastrophe risk,' comments Mr Frans Hoyer, transport
analyst with SG Warburg Securities.
But the restructuring of the shipowners' holdings also reflects their desire
to create corporate structures more acceptable to investors.
'Investors want clean structures which will be acceptable to the major stock
exchanges,' comments Mr Stainer. 'They don't want conflicts of interest with
remote management companies or promoters' fees.'
Investors do not want a return to the late 1980s, which saw the launch of a
number of closed-end shipping investment funds. Many of these funds charged
management fees and often took a stake of up to 30 per cent in any capital
appreciation of the vessels involved. 'This left a bad taste,' said Mr
McVicar. More importantly, many investors lost money.
The shipping industry is still dominated by private owners, but analysts
believe that recent fund-raisings reflect a shift towards putting ships into
publicly owned companies. Even some of the famously secretive Greek
shipowning families are moving in this direction.
But there are limits to this trend. Making a profit from shipowning can
still depend more on a feel for the market - spotting when to buy or sell a
vessel or an entire fleet - than on shaving 10 per cent off running costs by
better management.
And for all the excitement generated by the analysts' graphs of supply and
demand, the sector is still notoriously dependent on the unexpected. A large
oil spill or political upset in the Middle East could throw out all the
clever calculations.
</TEXT>
