<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / UK Company News: BTP improves 29% to Pounds 13m - Advance
assisted by three month contribution from MTM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BTP, the specialist chemical company which bought most of the assets of the
ailing MTM group for Pounds 106.7m in June, yesterday reported a 29 per cent
increase in interim profits reflecting the acquisition and organic growth.
Pre-tax profits increased to Pounds 13m in the six months to September 30
from Pounds 10.1m in the year-ago period. Turnover jumped 32 per cent to
Pounds 130.7m (Pounds 99m).
Earnings per share improved 12 per cent to 7.04p (6.26p) and the interim
dividend is lifted to 3.45p (3.25p).
BTP's share price closed 6p higher at 292p.
The MTM operations, part of the group for three months in the first half,
contributed Pounds 19.8m to turnover and Pounds 2.15m to operating profits
which grew to Pounds 13.9m (Pounds 10.3m). Excluding the seven MTM
businesses, all of which were profitable in the first half, operating
profits rose by 17.4 per cent.
Before the acquisition, two of MTM's businesses, one in the UK and one in
the US, had been losing about Pounds 2.5m a year. Mr Frank Buckley,
chairman, said the profit turnround had been achieved by discontinuing
lossmaking products and raising prices.
Following the acquisition BTP is now reporting fin-ancial details on four
sectors.
The largest of these, adhesives and textile coatings, reported sharply lower
operating profits of Pounds 2.79m (Pounds 3.8m), reflecting recession in
continental Europe, on turnover which expanded to Pounds 42.1m (Pounds
39.5m).
The performance chemicals division reported profits of Pounds 3.29m (Pounds
2.36m) on turnover of Pounds 24.3m (Pounds 15.6m). Excluding the MTM
operations profits improved by 11 per cent. The biocides and fine chemicals
division also showed strong growth with profits up at Pounds 4.43m (Pounds
1.99m) on turnover of Pounds 33.3m (Pounds 17.7m.).
The non-chemicals industrial division reported operating profits of Pounds
3.41m (Pounds 1.89m) on increased turnover of Pounds 31m (Pounds 26.2m)
helped by particularly strong growth in its safety harness business
reflecting tighter safety legislation in the US.
Net interest payments totalled Pounds 906,000 in the first half compared
with receipts of Pounds 75,000 in the year-ago period. The group ended
September with net borrowings of Pounds 33.8m against net borrowings of
Pounds 2m at the end of March.
Commenting on prospects Mr Buckley said, 'While we retain a cautious outlook
in the uncertain economic climate which prevails in a number of our markets,
we continue to view the future with confidence.'
</TEXT>
