<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / UK Company News: Framlington Russian fund
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By YURI BENDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Framlington, the London-based investment manager, is launching the first
ever quoted Russian investment fund. Lord Howe, the former foreign
secretary, will be its chairman.
Its portfolio will consist mainly of stakes in small to medium-sized joint
ventures between Russian and western companies. It has already targeted six
such ventures in food processing, high technology such as space and
electronics, and consumer goods such as textiles.
Other investments are likely in companies which service the Russian oil and
mining industries. The fund will buy stakes averaging 20 per cent, worth
typically between Dollars 500,000 and Dollars 4m.
Up to Dollars 75m (Pounds 50.3m) of the fund's shares will be placed with
institutions in the UK, continental Europe and North America. Subscriptions
to the closed-end, Luxembourg-regulated fund will close in mid-December
prior to share listing in Luxembourg and London.
The minimum stake is Dollars 100,000. The European Bank for Reconstruction
and Development is taking a Dollars 16m slice, and the International Finance
Corp is expected to take Dollars 8m.
Mr Connell Gallagher, Framlington's Russian investment analyst, forecasts
that the value of the fund's investments will grow by more than 30 per cent
a year over 10 years.
As well as political and economic risks, the prospectus warns institutions
that the fund's investments may be illiquid due to the lack of an
established Russian securities market. This may make it hard for the fund to
realise its full net asset value.
Mr Boris Jordan, Credit Suisse First Boston's Moscow-based director, says
the main risk of investing in Russia is the absence of a proper legal system
to protect shareholders' rights.
However, CSFB is positive about the fund's prospects: 'Russia is one of the
world's largest emerging economies,' says Mr Jordan. 'The sectors targeted
by the fund will be quite heavily invested over the next year, and most of
the interesting opportunities will quickly disappear.' Brokers to the fund
are Smith New Court, Bank Austria, and CCF Elysees Bourse, a division of
Credit Commercial de France, the French bank which is Framlington's majority
shareholder.
</TEXT>
