<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / UK Company News: Vacant space behind 19% decline at In Shops
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In Shops, the retail and office centres operator, saw profits dip 19 per
cent to Pounds 735,000 pre-tax in its first half to September 30, against
Pounds 903,000.
During the first half, Millbank, which with its chain of Job Lot stores was
acquired last August, contributed Pounds 1.64m to total turnover of Pounds
14.3m. Turnover of continuing operations was marginally higher at Pounds
11m.
The high level of vacant space in In Shops' centres caused profits to drop,
but recently there has been some improvement, opening the way to higher
profits in the second half.
The Birmingham-based group sold Executive Centres, its lossmaking chain of
serviced offices, shortly after the period-end for a nominal Pounds 1 to the
Fuchs family, which had been involved in the business before its acquisition
by In Shops.
The disposal appears in the accounts as a loss of Pounds 5.04m which is more
than offset by a provision of Pounds 5.52m set up in the previous year.
The disposal, combined with Millbank, has repositioned In Shops as a retail
specialist. Next month Job Lot will expand from the north into the Midlands
and south of England.
Earnings per share on continuing activities were 1.25p, against 1.7p.
The interim dividend, up from 0.66p to 0.7p, is being paid on capital
enlarged by the share sale to pay for Millbank.
</TEXT>
