<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / AEG acts to move out of the red
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES and CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT, STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AEG is to sell its household appliances business to Electrolux of Sweden in
a radical shake-out designed to return the loss-making Daimler-Benz
subsidiary to the break-even point in 1995.
Other projects outlined by AEG yesterday include joint ventures with General
Electric of the US, a new structure for its railways operations,
collaboration deals, and the disposal of 'fringe' businesses in lighting and
meters.
Mr Georg Stockl, AEG chairman, said the changes would reduce turnover from
DM11bn (Pounds 4.3bn) last year to DM9.3bn, and the payroll from 60,000 to
48,000. The company would be known as AEG Daimler-Benz Industrie.
Mr Stockl gave no details of the price expected for the appliances business,
in which Electrolux already has a 10 per cent stake, but said the Swedish
group had agreed to keep open the company's three German factories.
The deal would give Electrolux an estimated 35 per cent of the German white
goods market, compared with 20 per cent, and would increase its share of the
European market from 25 per cent to some 30 per cent.
Completion of the deal depends on approval by the European Commission
competition office. However, the group does not foresee regulatory problems,
partly because most of its sales in Germany are generated through an
intermediary which is free to choose a different supplier. Early signals
suggest the authorities are satisfied that there is enough heavyweight
competition, such as Whirlpool and Bosch-Siemens.
Mr Stockl said a letter of intent had been signed with GE for the US group
to take a majority stake in AEG's low voltage switchgear business. GE was
also to manage a joint venture embracing both companies' interests in drives
automation.
AEG is known to be seeking a partner for its loss-making DM1.5bn-a-year
railways business. Further savings are expected from intra-group deals under
which AEG is to take full control of Daimler's micro-electronics business.
The changes at AEG are part of the rationalisation of Daimler-Benz,
Germany's biggest industrial concern. Its Deutsche-Aerospace (Dasa)
subsidiary, for instance, recently announced the closure of six German sites
and warned of further cuts.
World stock markets, Page 41
</TEXT>
