<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / NFC to raise Pounds 263m in first rights issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NFC, the UK-based transport and logistics group, yesterday launched a Pounds
263m rights issue - the first since the group was privatised by an employee
buy-out in 1982.
After the issue, NFC will have net cash of Pounds 89.4m - a turnround from
gearing of 53 per cent. It plans to expand its distribution and house-moving
businesses internationally.
The rights issue reflects NFC's unusual share structure. About 45 per cent
of the company's shares are in private hands and 85 per cent of the group's
32,000 employees are shareholders.
The 1-for-4 issue is priced at 195p and NFC's shares closed 13p higher at
247p. Small shareholders who do not wish to take up their rights will be
offered 14p per new share to which they are entitled by BZW, which is
underwriting the issue.
Mr Peter Sherlock, NFC's new chief executive, said the issue would increase
the number of shares available to institutional investors, but he stressed
he did not want to lose NFC's distinctive culture - which includes an annual
meeting attended by more than 1,000 shareholders.
He said: 'It is much easier to articulate a philosophy of enhancing
shareholder value if 85 per cent of the employees are shareholders. But we
must not let it act as a restraint on the business, which employees also
understand.'
Current employees - who constitute 14 per cent of the share register - have
double voting rights, but only so long as their total stake is more than 10
per cent. Even if no employees take up their rights, their share of the
register would only fall to 11 per cent, so there is no immediate threat to
their special position, but it is clearly on the way out.
The 14p per new share being offered to investors with fewer than 150,000
shares is the midpoint between the rights issue price and the theoretical
ex-rights price, based on Tuesday's closing price of 234p, minus the
grossed-up dividend for which the new shares do not rank. BZW will
underwrite 62 per cent of the shares at 195p and the 38 per cent held by
smaller shareholders at the higher price of 209p. Cazenove and UBS are joint
brokers.
NFC announced the rights issue alongside annual results which showed a 17
per cent increase in pre-tax profits to Pounds 104.9m.
Results, Page 26
Lex, Page 24
</TEXT>
