<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / Warning from Courtaulds Textiles
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Courtaulds Textiles fell 10 per cent yesterday after the UK group
warned that pre-tax profits for the year about to end would be below market
expectations.
The announcement was an unwelcome swansong from Mr Martin Taylor, the
youthful chairman of Courtaulds Textiles, who next month starts his new role
as chief executive of Barclays, the UK's largest bank. However, Mr Taylor,
41, who was head-hunted for the Barclays job partly because of his skill at
dealing with the press and City analysts, denied feeling any embarrassment
about giving the profits warning only three weeks before his departure. 'I'd
rather handle it than leave it to my colleagues.'
Courtaulds Textiles said it was unlikely profits for the year to December 31
would match last year's Pounds 39m. Analysts, who had cut their estimates to
Pounds 41m-Pounds 43m after lower than expected interim profits of Pounds
13.7m, yesterday trimmed their full-year forecasts to about Pounds 37m. The
shares closed 54p lower at 489p.
The group had reported difficult conditions in continental Europe in
September. It said yesterday that trading had deteriorated further in
October and November.
Mr Taylor said: 'In the UK, although there has been some recovery, the level
of early autumn activity has not been maintained.'
A particular problem was caused by a new factory near Derby in which the
group had invested Pounds 10m to make Aristoc stockings. Teething problems
prevented the plant reaching full capacity, so it lost sales and profits in
the peak pre-Christmas manufacturing period.
Mr Taylor was worried about the outlook for continental Europe, which last
year accounted for 18 per cent of sales: 'We made no money in Europe in the
first half and we are not going to make any in the second.'
Two thirds of group profits were usually made in the second half. Only when
management accounts for November were produced last week did the size of the
shortfall became clear.
The board was still expecting to recommend an increase in the final
dividend.
Lex, Page 24
London SE, Page 44
</TEXT>
