<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / Partial victory in US trade talks claimed by Balladur
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN and DAVID DODWELL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Edouard Balladur, France's prime minister, yesterday declared a partial
victory in trade talks with the US, and said he would put any overall Gatt
accord before parliament early next week in a vote that he seems confident
of winning.
'We have emerged from our isolation without conceding anything essential,'
he told cheering deputies from his conservative coalition. Opposition
Socialists and farm union leaders complained, however, of a cave-in.
Agriculture 'is no longer an obstacle' to agreement because Europe's deal
with the US this week was 'satisfactory in a great deal more than half' of
it, he said. His most positive statement to date on Gatt helped push the
franc back through its former European exchange rate floor of FFr3.4305 to
the D-Mark, which France was forced to abandon in August.
Mr Balladur, however, is keeping up pressure on his European Union partners
to compensate France for what it failed to get from the US. 'I hope for a
Gatt agreement, but I cannot give you the certainty of one,' he told French
deputies. He said the next three days, covering the EU summit starting in
Brussels on Friday, 'will be decisive'.
Mr Balladur rang Mr Helmut Kohl, the German chancellor, on Tuesday night and
Mr Ruud Lubbers, the Dutch prime minister, yesterday morning to lobby them
on French demands for tougher European protection against unfair trade and
for more money to compensate farmers.
Mr Alain Juppe, the foreign minister who also holds the key political job of
secretary-general of Mr Balladur's RPR Gaullist party, warned that the EU
might have to increase the farm share of its budget, a move sure to be
resisted by Britain and the Netherlands.
Meanwhile, US and EU negotiators in Geneva began a series of bilateral
meetings explaining details of the US-EU deal to other countries involved in
the Uruguay Round of international trade talks. Gatt officials moved to
finalise texts for a global trade accord that has until now been blocked by
US-EU disagreements.
Mr Germain Denis, who chairs the Gatt committee drawing up a global market
access deal, briefed a group of less than 20 countries on a final package
that he hopes to table before all 116 countries in the Round this morning.
With a tariff-cutting market access deal close to settlement, negotiators
moved on to the outstanding disputed issues - mainly efforts to open up
financial services markets, and controversial US proposals enabling tax
discrimination against foreign companies.
Hopes rises for pact on aircraft subsidies, Page 6
</TEXT>
