<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Today's programme in BBC2's admirable series Human Rights, Human Wrongs is
presented by American playwright Arthur Miller. He declares that freedom of
information is the touchstone of all the freedoms enshrined in the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights, but points out that imprisonment is now being
replaced by violence, 'censorship by the bullet', as the favoured means used
by repressive governments to silence writers and reporters (8.20).
Episode 1 of ITV's series Hollywood Women, which looked from the hype as
though it was going to be just a good excuse for eyeing lots of gorgeous
bodies, turned out to be both better and worse than that. Worse in that it
was edited into insultingly brief soundbites, better in that it had a
perfectly serious point to make about plastic surgery and the obsession with
eternal youth. Today's programme (9.00) is about women and the casting
couch.
Channel 4's documentary series The Plague looks at the formation of Aids
pressure groups and the reactions of government bodies (9.00).
</TEXT>
