<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / National one-day stoppage in public services proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A one-day strike in the public sector, probably on April 11, has been
proposed by the NUCPS civil service union, David Goodhart writes. The move
may win support from the Trades Union Congress's public services committee
early next month.
The executive of Unison, the 1.5m-strong public service union, is this
weekend expected to back the strike call. In spite of reservations from some
other unions, such as the GMB general union, Unison's backing could be
enough to swing TUC support behind the day.
The strike would be a quasi-political protest against government policy on
pay, jobs, market testing and privatisation throughout the public sector. It
might therefore be ruled unlawful even if proper strike ballots were
conducted.
Opponents of strike action such as Mr John Edmonds, general secretary of the
GMB, say the government would relish a legal and industrial conflict with
the unions in the run-up to the local elections in May, and would seek to
associate Labour authorities with the disruption.
Opponents of action also say that if the day of action succeeded, it would
present the wrong image of trade unionism at a time when unions are trying
to persuade their members to retain 'check-off' - the automatic deduction of
union dues by employers.
'I fear the movement is about to sleep-walk into a disaster,' said one
official.
Supporters of strike action say there is no other way to effectively express
the anger of members. They point to the relative success of the day of
action against market testing by civil servants on November 5.
Mr John Monks, TUC general secretary, is unlikely to be enthusiastic about
action but will lead it if this is what unions want.
Unions will try to minimise inconvenience to the public, although the rail
unions are likely to join in. Emergency services will be excluded.
</TEXT>
<XX>
