<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / Sunday shopping campaigners rejoice
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Supporters of Sunday opening were jubilant after last night's vote in the
Commons to allow all shops to open for at least six hours.
Baroness Jay, chairman of the Shopping Hours Reform Council, which proposed
the partial deregulation option, said the vote 'reflected the wishes of the
majority of the people'. She added: 'It provides for a good, sound and
popular law.'
Mr David Quarmby, joint managing director of J. Sainsbury, the UK's largest
superstore chain, said: 'The main people who will benefit from this are the
millions of people who already shop on Sundays and will be able to go on
doing so.'
Asda, the UK's fourth-largest food superstore group, said it was pleased
that the vote had produced a 'clear-cut decision'. The company said it
already opened about 150 of its 200 stores on Sundays, which had become the
third busiest day of the week.
Mr Nigel Whittaker, executive director of Kingfisher, parent company of B&amp;Q,
Superdrug, Woolworth and Comet, said he was 'delighted that parliament has
reflected the feeling of the country'. The option chosen was 'practical,
workable and provides a permanent solution'.
Workers' groups also welcomed the decision. Ms Julie Trussler, chairwoman of
the National Association of Sunday Shopworkers, which has campaigned for the
right to work on Sundays, said the vote would 'safeguard the jobs of 140,000
Sunday shopworkers'.
But Usdaw, the largest shopworkers' union, which switched support at the
last minute from the Keep Sunday Special Campaign to the option which was
adopted, warned its support was 'crucially linked to the worker protection
element'. It added: 'We will now be fighting hard to ensure our members are
protected against exploitation, and critically, get double-time payments for
working on Sunday.'
The Consumers' Association said it was 'partially pleased' with the vote, as
it had supported total deregulation. Mr Derek Prentice, assistant director,
predicted that parliament would have to return to the issue in a few years'
time 'when people realise that total deregulation is really the only
complete answer'.
The vote was a bitter disappointment for those who had campaigned to limit
Sunday opening, warning that even partial deregulation would destroy the
unique character of Sundays.
Mr Michael Schluter, director of the Keep Sunday Special Campaign, said MPs
had been victims of 'a huge deception', as the provisions on worker
protection in the bill were inadequate and unworkable.
The campaign would be 'exploring all the avenues we can use to lessen the
impact of the bill on the most vulnerable sectors of society', including
shopworkers, small shopkeepers, and those on low incomes living near city
centres.
Marks and Spencer, one of the UK's leading retailers and the driving force
behind Retailers for Shops Act Reform, which joined forces with the Keep
Sunday Special Campaign to support limited opening, said it could 'now get
to work knowing there is a solution, even though it is not the one we
favoured'.
The clothing and food chain said it would now be forced to open some stores
on Sundays to avoid losing market share, but would wait for the bill to
receive royal assent next year.
</TEXT>
