<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / Clash of Titans draws the crowds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Baroness Thatcher's appear-ance before the Scott inquiry was billed as a
constitutional battle of the Titans.
In the blue corner, immaculately turned out in a dark green tailored suit
and double rope of pearls, was the first British ex-premier to appear before
a public judicial inquiry.
Facing her, in the grey corner, were Ms Presiley Baxendale QC, wearing a
loud houndstooth black and white check jacket, and Lord Justice Scott, a
picture of judicial gravitas in half glasses and double breasted suit.
Their goal was to wrestle from her whether sales of military equipment by UK
companies to Iraq during the late 1980s, in apparent contravention of stated
government policy, were made with or without her knowledge and approval.
The arena was Number 1 Buckingham Gate, once a seedy hotel, now refurbished
as a slightly vulgar government office, with brass chandeliers and wood
panelling.
For the first time since the inquiry began six months ago, it was packed.
Most of the crowd were journalists, who had queued since 7.30am to secure
places.
When the contest began at 10am, Lady Thatcher appeared tired and defensive.
Ms Baxendale - whom Lady Thatcher insisted on calling 'Miss' in a slightly
deprecating tone - was enthusiastic and rigorously analytical - qualities
which have terrified the officials and ministers she has already examined.
But appearances were deceptive. Lady Thatcher had carefully studied the 76
pages of questions the judge sent her a month ago. She parried every attack
and on one occasion congratulated herself for providing a convincing reply
to the one question she had not 'spotted' in advance.
Her overall strategy was simple. The most hands-on prime minister in recent
history argued that she never got involved in the detailed application of
the arms sales policy.
Lord Scott looked at her quizzically when she repeatedly said that she
concerned herself with 'policy-making', never with 'detailed
administration'. But he had no evidence to the contrary.
In six-and-a-half hours of cross-examination, only five substantive
questions were put, which can be summarised as follows:
Baxendale: Why was there a gap of a year between the formulation of a new
policy banning sales of arms to both Iran and Iraq in late 1984 and its
disclosure to parliament in October 1985?
Thatcher: Don't know.
Baxendale: Should parliament have been told earlier? Thatcher: That might
have been preferable because it would have saved me a lot of this bother.
Baxendale: After the Gulf war ended, official policy appears to have been
changed so that sales of some military equipment to Iraq was now permitted.
Is that so and why was parliament told that the 1985 policy was still being
followed?
Thatcher: On the one hand, I was not told of a change of policy. On the
other, it seems to me - from my subsequent examination of government
documents - that although there may appear to have been a change in policy,
in fact there was a change in circumstances leading to a 'modicum of
flexibility' in the implementation of the existing policy.
Baxendale: Were you informed about sales of machine tools, which have
military applications, by the engineering company Matrix Churchill?
Thatcher: No.
Baxendale: Why were you and other ministers unaware of information gathered
by the intelligence services that the engineering company Matrix Churchill
was selling to Iraq equipment with a military use?
Thatcher: The system did not work properly.
Baxendale: Were you aware of warnings from the intelligence services that
sales of military equipment to Jordan were being diverted to Iraq?
Thatcher: No.
By four o'clock Ms Baxendale was looking tired and had lost her customary
eloquence. Lady Thatcher was positively buoyant. When told there was to be a
short break, she looked annoyed. 'I do hope we go on till we finish,' she
challenged. Ms Baxendale may have met her match.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    IQZ  Iraq, Middle East.
</CN>
