<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / Cards may be 'smart', but are they attractive?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
National Westminster Bank has been demonstrating in a mocked-up sitting room
the 'smart card' which it hopes to establish as a global substitute for
cash.
The phone on which cash can be transferred to the card sits by a bookshelf
containing Enid Blyton's Mysteries and a book called Great Disasters.
For the moment, the prospects of smart cards remain a mystery. Whether the
Mondex card will become a disaster or a triumph for NatWest depends on the
reaction of about 30,000 consumers and 1,000 retailers in Swindon. Their
reaction in a pilot run with British Telecommunications in 1995 will
determine its future.
The Mondex vision is compelling, both for consumers and for banks which
spend increasing amounts on handling cash. NatWest hopes that consumers will
adjust to a world in which they load cards with cash from phones and
electronic terminals in up to 30 currencies, and use the cards as cash
tokens.
The heart of the system is a computer chip which sits on a plastic card and
can store electronic value in up to five currencies. The holder can load the
card from a bank cash machine, a retailer's terminal, or from a telephone
with a card reader which may cost about Dollars 200 (Pounds 134).
Once the cash is transferred from the holder's account to the card it can be
spent at any retail outlet which has the right card reader. There is no
personal identification number (PIN), so someone who drops the card in the
street can easily lose the whole amount, just like losing cash.
Security is provided by the ability to 'lock' the card so that it cannot be
used. This 'locking' can also be done on a plastic 'wallet' with its own
internal chip which two Japanese electronics companies have built for
NatWest. This can also be used to transfer money from one card to another.
Users will be able to check the balance on the card by using a reader built
into a keyring (pictured right).
Yet Mondex is fraught with risks. Older people may not like carrying around
a card which a thief can use like cash unless it has been electronically
'locked'. Equally, NatWest and its partner Midland may not make a return on
a large capital investment if other banks simply set up competing smart-card
systems.
The heart of the appeal for banks is twofold. First, they may remove cash
from the enormously expensive clearing systems which operate in all
developed countries. The cost of cash transmission in the UK clearing system
alone has been estimated at Pounds 2bn a year.
Second, they may establish a form of payment which is suited to a wider
range of consumers and retail outlets than credit and debit cards. Such
cards are limited to creditworthy consumers who can be trusted not to
overspend, but the Mondex system simply provides a limited amount of cash.
Mr Tim Jones, the NatWest executive who thought of the idea, said: 'There is
a much broader opportunity than with credit and debit because anyone can
hold cash.' He said the technology suited cash-based outlets such as taxis,
fast-food stores and small retailers well.
The bank emphasises the use for families which could hand out set sums to
children using the electronic wallet. But it argues strongly against the
notion that it is simply an electronic card for feckless folk without access
to credit.
The hardest task will be to persuade consumers of the benefit. The ability
to load cash from home may appeal. The easy access to foreign currency is
also convenient. But a lot may depend on the bank's eventual pricing
strategy.
Having to buy equipment to participate in a card-based system when cash
accounts are free might not hold much appeal. But NatWest will have to make
it attractive enough to establish the brand clearly.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>National Westminster Bank.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6141 Personal Credit Institutions.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
