<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / OFT rejects newspaper distribution complaint
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Monopolies and Mergers Commission will today reject complaints that
national newspaper distribution is a monopoly that acts against the public
interest.
In the latest of a series of investigations going back to 1976 the
commission has decided that newspaper distributors such as WH Smith, John
Menzies and Surridge Dawson operate an efficient service that gets the
largest number of newspapers to the public at a reasonable cost.
After looking at the industry for more than a year the commission has come
up with only one significant recommendation for change - that newsagents
should be allowed to 'sub-retail' newspapers to others.
Some newsagents sell on papers to others and split the discount. This is
seen as a 'pirate' operation and discouraged by the distributors.
The commission decided that some sub-retailing on a 'sensible' and local
basis would act as a safety valve for those who wanted to sell papers but
could not get supplies.
One of the main pressures for change has come from small convenience and
grocery stores, which want to sell papers but have generally been refused
supplies on the grounds that they are in areas already served by newsagents.
VG Distributors, the independent high-street grocery chain, told the
commission inquiry that the market was 'rigged' and that fixed newspaper
distribution territories, often operating on an exclusive franchise basis,
should be dismantled.
VG said it was campaigning on behalf of more than 40,000 convenience stores
which could not get newspapers even though, they argued, newsagents were
increasingly entering the grocery sector by selling items such as milk,
bread and baked beans.
A number of ideas which would have opened up the newspaper retail market
more fully to outsiders were rejected.
Professor Samuel Eilon, a member of the commission panel, suggested a system
of 'minimum list values' - setting a guaranteed minimum of copies that would
go to non-traditional outlets with the Office of Fair Trading increasing the
total each year. The idea was rejected by the majority.
Proposals for a cash-and-carry scheme, allowing prospective sellers of
newspapers to pick up copies direct from wholesalers at their own expense,
were also rejected.
Newspaper distribution was first referred to the commission in 1976 and its
report two years later found that a complex monopoly did exist, but that it
was not against the public interest to limit the number of retailers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
