<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / Treasury confident about recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The economic recovery looks set to continue with inflationary pressures
staying muted, according to the UK Treasury's latest monthly monetary
report.
The document, prepared for yesterday's monthly discussion of monetary
conditions between Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr Eddie George,
the governor of the Bank of England, notes that 'recent monthly indicators
confirm the picture of recovery continuing'. It adds that UK producer price
inflation 'suggests inflationary pressures remain subdued'.
Although the 40-page report does not discuss policy, avoids analysis and is
generally little more than a description of all the money, inflation and
activity indicators published over the past month, it strikes one or two
upbeat notes.
It judges that the trend in retail sales, as measured by the Central
Statistical Office and the Confederation of British Industry, 'remains
firmly upward'. Its overall view of the CBI's monthly industrial trends
survey is that it implies 'total demand is holding up well following
significant improvements earlier in the year'.
It warns that official statistics showing that manufacturing output in
volume terms was broadly flat in the third quarter might be 'slightly
distorted' by the introduction of the European Union's Intrastat figures for
export prices. These are used to construct the manufacturing output index.
The report notes that the fall in the annual rate of underlying inflation,
as measured by the retail prices index minus mortgage interest payments, to
2.8 per cent in October from 3.3 per cent in September, has fully reversed
the autumn rises from the summer's 25-year low. 'Most significantly, food
and petrol prices fell between September and October having risen over the
same period last year'. It adds that the fall in food prices preceded the
latest announcements of price reductions by large supermarkets.
The report points to only a very slight increase in producer price inflation
between September and October, although it says 'anecdotal evidence suggests
some businesses are still waiting for markets to strengthen before passing
on input-related costs'.
</TEXT>
