<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / Bar's monopoly ended: Solicitors in private practice win
right to appear in higher courts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Barristers' 200-year monopoly on advocacy in the higher courts was broken
yesterday when solicitors in private practice won their battle for wider
rights to present cases.
The decision by Lord Mackay, the Lord Chancellor, and England's four most
senior judges to approve the Law Society's application for wider advocacy
rights means solicitors could be appearing in higher courts by next spring.
At present they can only appear in magistrates' and county courts.
The government legislated more than two years ago to give solicitors the
right to appear in the higher courts, but the issue has been deadlocked by
resistance from the Bar and judges.
Mr Rodger Pannone, the Law Society's president, said it was delighted with
the decision. 'Clients will no longer be forced to employ a separate lawyer
for higher court advocacy,' he said.
The society said it was disappointed that Lord Mackay and the judges had
deferred their decision on wider advocacy rights for solicitors working in
the Crown Prosecution Service, the government legal service, and in
commerce, finance and industry.
Although the society's application included employed solicitors, the judges
felt unable to decide because of incomplete advice from the Lord
Chancellor's advisory committee.
The committee said it could not advise on whether employed lawyers should be
given the right to appear in criminal trials until the 1990 Courts and Legal
Services Act had been changed to restrict the amount of advocacy work done
by Crown Prosecution Service and government lawyers. Lord Mackay has ruled
out changes to the act and asked it to look again at the issue.
Mrs Barbara Mills QC, director of public prosecutions, said she was pleased
that the lord chancellor had not ruled out extending rights to Crown
Prosecution Service lawyers. They would continue to push for extended
rights, she said.
The decision was welcomed by many City law firms, which have been gearing up
for advocacy work in the High Court.
Solicitors who have the necessary experience in advocacy, either as
part-time judges or who have earlier practised as barristers, will be able
to appear in the High Court almost immediately. But most will have to
complete two Law Society training courses and it could be 1995 before they
qualify to appear in the crown court, High Court, Appeal Court, or before
the Lords.
</TEXT>
<XX>
