<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / Saunders 'has case' to fight charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Ernest Saunders, the former Guinness chairman convicted of fraud over the
company's 1986 takeover of Distillers, has won the first round of his
attempt to use European law to challenge his prosecution, John Mason writes.
The European Commission on Human Rights has ruled that Mr Saunders has a
partially admissible case.
Mr Saunders is claiming he was denied a fair hearing at his trial because
the prosecution used evidence against him which was gained from his
interviews with Department of Trade and Industry inspectors.
During these interviews he was compelled to answer questions. He claims the
use of transcripts during his trial therefore infringed provisions in the
European Convention on Human Rights which protects against
self-incrimination.
