<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / Regulations fix pension sales method
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The selling of personal pensions is a highly regulated business.
Firms which sell private pensions must first be authorised by one of the
self-regulating organisations which monitor the retail financial services
industry. Sales agents must be 'fit and proper', a term which, among other
things, generally excludes bankrupts.
Sales agents are expected to be trained to understand the products they sell
and the population for which they might be suitable. Financial services
rules bar them from trying to sell unsuitable policies. Insurance companies
have had to pay substantial sums in compensation to people who bought
inappropriate plans.
Sales agents can be directly employed by a provider, or be a tied agent who,
although not employed directly, sells one provider's products exclusively,
or an independent financial adviser, who sells the best products of a group
of providers.
Direct and tied sales agents do not operate unsupervised, at least in
theory. Insurance companies are responsible for monitoring the activities of
their sales staff and ensuring that they comply with all regulations.
Independent financial advisers, on the other hand, may be monitored if they
are employed by a large chain. The only check on individual firms is
monitoring by Fimbra, the self-regulating body for the industry.
In making sales pitches agents must first identify themselves, stating
whether they are independent or tied to one company. They must then conduct
a 'fact find' of an individual's financial situation and current and future
needs. Any thorough review would require sales agents to ask about existing
pension arrangements.
These fact finds - or the lack of them - have most troubled regulators. It
is believed that up to 80 per cent of the pension transfer files examined
had too little information about clients and their former schemes for agents
to be able to make a suitable recommendation.
In completing a fact find to assess a potential transfer from an employer's
scheme the sales agent would have to ask for details of its benefits, the
contribution levels of both the employee and the employer, and the scope for
so-called discretionary benefits which allow trustees to give more generous
pensions than those formally described in the trust deed. The agent would
also need to know the number of years the individual had been a member of
the scheme, the number of years to retirement and plans for any job changes.
The sales agent would have to compute the pension benefits received under
the employer's scheme and compare them with those expected from a personal
pension.
Only after this procedure could a sales agent offer best advice about
pensions transfers and make a proposal to sell a specific policy.
Individuals want personal pensions for a variety of reasons, of course, but
the sales agent must advise clients exactly what they might be giving up.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
TIMETABLE:
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
July 1988:   Tax incentives to encourage individuals to opt out of the
             State Earnings Related Pension Scheme become effective,
             spurring boom in personal pensions.
July 1992:   Lautro, the regulator, issues enforcement bulleting 16
             saying that under most circumstances, those in occupational
             schemes should stay there. Orders review of early
             terminations of personal pension policies - to later find
             that 50,000 have lapsed in the third quarter of 1992,
             all two years-old or under. Fellow regulator Fimbra issues
             similar sales guidance, but no retrospective review.
December 3,
  1993:      News breaks that inquiry under way by Securities and
             Investments Board.
Yesterday:   Committee named.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
