<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / Prudential chief takes firm line on payouts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Leading pension providers do not intend to provide compensation to people
sold their products wrongly by independent financial advisers if Mr Mick
Newmarch, Prudential chief executive, is any guide.
Mr Newmarch emphasises his commitment to recompensing the 'handful' of
people who have suffered after poor advice from the company's direct sales
force to transfer out of occupational schemes and buy Prudential pensions.
However, he is clear that his company is not responsible for independent
advisers' actions.
The Prudential is the UK's largest life insurer and one of the largest
pension providers, with 850,000 pension holders and Pounds 65bn of assets
under management. It has sold most of its pension products through its own
direct sales force of about 8,000, with little business through
independents.
'An (independent financial adviser) is sorting products from a whole variety
of providers on the basis of his view of the best advice for his customer,'
he said. 'If my contract is the best in his eyes and he chooses to use it,
that's presumably good. If he misuses it, I can't be held responsible for
that, can I?'
The Prudential's exposure to this area of business is limited. It has some
45,000 personal pension holders transferred from occupational schemes since
1988, out of a market of between 400,000 and 500,000.
Yet scale does depend on perspective. Mr Paul Trickett, the head of pensions
in the Mineworkers' Pension Scheme, said some Pounds 58m had been
transferred to the Prudential from that scheme since 1988.
Mr Newmarch is unapologetic about the legitimate argument for personal
pensions as well as proud of the Prudential's own record in training,
procedures and setting standards for its sales force. The Prudential says
the number of cases investigated for wrong advice so far has been about 100
at most.
Even so, he recognises that the damage to people's perception of the
industry could still affect his company.
'If the whole industry is being held as not properly organised and taking
advantage of people's ignorance and innocence and so on, then at some point
nobody escapes that general proposition,' he said.
But he underlined that responsibility did not rest with the industry alone.
Those such as the trustees of occupational schemes and schemes' consulting
actuaries also had duties to provide proper information to aid decisions to
transfer out of an occupational scheme.
'The responsibility in all this is a very complex series of interrelated
events,' he said. On the basis that most of the life industry tried to
behave properly, 'then where things go awry it is for a whole variety of
complex reasons'.
'At the margin - I hope it's the margin - some companies have been
uncontrolled in taking advantage of what they saw as a market opportunity,
and the regulator's job is to stop that.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Prudential Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6371 Pension, Health, and Welfare Funds.
</IN>
<XX>
