<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / Cancer 'not high' in N-test veterans
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Servicemen who took part in British nuclear weapon tests in the South
Pacific during the 1950s are not suffering an excess of cancer, says a study
to be published tomorrow.
The report by the National Radiological Protection Board and Imperial Cancer
Research Fund is a follow-up to a controversial study of 22,000 bomb test
veterans, published in 1988. It had found more leukaemia cases among men who
had witnessed the open-air explosions than among a control group of
servicemen who were not present, although overall death rates in the two
groups were similar.
The new study, supervised by Sir Richard Doll, concludes that the excess of
leukaemia was a statistical artefact.
