FT  09 DEC 93 / Histadrut movement decides to go ahead with one day strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Israel's Histadrut labour movement has decided to go ahead with a one-day
nationwide public-sector strike today which could paralyse the country,
despite a government promise to freeze its privatisation programme for up to
four weeks pending further talks with unions, Julian Ozanne writes from
Jerusalem.
The move came as a restructuring plan for the financially-troubled Israel
Aircraft Industries, Israel's largest employer, was agreed, which should
release hundred of millions of dollars of government aid in a rescue
package.
Up to 100,000 workers in government-owned companies, including electricity,
telephone and water, state-controlled radio and TV, and postal and airport
services have been asked to obey the strike call.
But later, a Tel Aviv court ruled that postal and airport workers were
forbidden to take part. The unions want greater involvement in privatisation
plans.
