<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / Republics face threat of reprisals: Contenders line up for
next Sunday's democratic parliamentary elections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD and LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Senior Russian politicians yesterday threatened reprisals against leaders of
republics who have called for a No vote in Sunday's referendum on a draft
constitution for Russia. Fears are growing that the draft will not be
adopted and that a new period of political instability will result.
At the same time, a statement from the leadership of the rebel Russian
republic of Chechnya, the most extreme of the anti-Moscow republics and the
only one which has banned all voting on Sunday, said President Boris Yeltsin
had made a declaration of war by threatening to tighten border controls and
cut rail communications.
Chechnya, under General Dzhokar Dudayev, has declared complete independence
and is a centre of anti-Russian agitation in the north Caucasian region.
However several other republics, led by Tatarstan, insist on the right of
sovereignty and most party leaders have come out against the constitution.
The warnings of reprisals, and of chaos if the referendum were not passed,
reflects intense concern within the Yeltsin camp that the constitution will
not be adopted. It requires a 50 per cent vote on a turnout of at least 50
per cent of the voters - a result originally considered attainable but now,
in the face if widespread apathy and even hostility, thought to be in
danger.
Mr Sergei Filatov, Mr Yeltsin's chief of staff, warned the presidents of
Russia's republics who have called for a No vote that the armed forces,
security forces and interior ministry were 'seriously concerned' by the
opposition to the constitution, especially by the leaders of Tatarstan,
Bashkortostan and Tuva. A government reaction to this opposition was now
being prepared, he said.
'Those who are making war on the constitution. . . . should take care of the
unity of the Russian federation, or we shall lead our state to catastrophe.'
Mr Nikolai Medvedev, head of the president's department for relations with
the Russian regions, warned still more pointedly: 'Even after the tragic
events (of October 4 when the Russian parliament was shelled by the army)
they are not behaving responsibly in what they say (and). . . . they are
answerable before their consciences and the state, as state officials.'
Mr Yegor Gaidar, head of the liberal group Russia's Choice, said in a
newspaper interview that the constitution 'bears the stamp of the events of
October 3-4' and that it was far from perfect. 'All the same, I'm deeply
convinced that the risk of it's not being adopted is incomparably greater
than the risk form its imperfections.'
Mr Anatoly Sobchak, mayor of St Petersburg and a leader of the Movement of
Democratic Reforms, which supports the constitution, said he feared the
referendum would not be passed. 'The constitution has not been properly
presented, no explanatory work on he necessity to adopt it has been done and
the overwhelming majority of voters either know nothing or too little about
it,' he said.
Western observers, now gathering in Moscow to review the progress of the
voting on Sunday, generally believe it is 'within the bounds of the
democratic arena' - in the worlds of Mrs Herta Daubler-Gmelin, a German
Social Democrat deputy. However, they stress that it will work only if the
parties and the political class refrain from extreme methods and support
reform.
</TEXT>
