<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 93 / Pension review may affect 400,000: Study finds sales rules
were not followed in four out of five cases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Four out of five personal pensions sold to people transferring out of
employers' schemes into private plans were taken out without agents seeking
enough information to give proper advice, according to an independent study.
Up to 400,000 people could be affected and several hundred million pounds in
compensation in total may have to be paid by life insurers, banks and
building societies.
Mr Andrew Large, chairman of the Securities and investments Board, the
City's chief watchdog, yesterday gave details of the SIB's pension transfer
review announced last week. He spelt out how compensation would be handled
and what measures would be taken to ensure that customers would not be sold
unsuitable personal pensions in future.
An advisory committee made up largely of chairmen of the relevant
professional and trade associations, and chaired by former senior civil
servant Sir Douglas Wass, will assist the SIB board.
The pilot study, which points to widespread abuse in the sale of personal
pensions, was commissioned from the accountancy firm KPMG Peat Marwick. KPMG
sought to assess how many people were at risk of disadvantage from having
followed poor advice. The report is to be published before Christmas.
It found that in 80 per cent of cases examined, sales agents had not
properly complied with regulatory requirements for selling pensions in this
way.
If this reflects wider practice, some 400,000 cases could be re-opened with
sales agents. Up to 500,000 individuals have transferred out of employers'
schemes and into personal pensions.
Many of these cases will have to be raised with the individual customers, to
establish who might be worse off in retirement as a result of following poor
advice.
Mr Large acknowledged that people covered by the review who had already
retired might be receiving less income than they were entitled to, but he
emphasised that all those affected would be fully recompensed.
'Those who may have transferred their pension provision on the basis of
wrong advice will not be harmed by waiting for reliable solutions to
emerge,' he said.
Ministers face particular embarrassment from the political emphasis that was
placed on the benefit of taking out a personal pension in terms of
flexibility.
Mr Anthony Nelson, Treasury economic secretary, welcomed the latest move,
but added: 'Should the further investigations now under way reveal that any
clients have suffered financial loss as a result of bad advice, I have made
it clear to SIB that the government expects effective remedies to be put in
place promptly.'
A steering group, made up of the heads of financial regulators and some
professional bodies, will draw up remedies for the harm that has been done,
and recommend measures to prevent future problems.
One difficult area will be pensions sold on bad advice from independent
financial advisers. Mr Mick Newmarch, chief executive of the Prudential, one
of the largest pensions providers, said yesterday he was not responsible for
any failure by independent advisers to give proper advice in selling a
Prudential pension.
The steering group will recommend new sales rules to the SIB board by the
end of February. It will make recommendations on compensation by the end of
June, and SIB will publish its intended course of action in July.
Sales agents will be able to sell pensions to people transferring out of
occupational schemes under the existing regulations until new rules are set,
but Mr Large warned that they must take extra care 'to give sound and full
advice'.
What to do if you think you have suffered, Page 8
Lex, Page 24
</TEXT>
