<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 93 / International Company News: Ameritech service appeal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ameritech, the Chicago-based local telephone company, yesterday took the
first step to becoming the first Baby Bell regional telecommunications group
to enter the long-distance calling market. It has asked the US Justice
Department for permission to offer a long-distance service, initially on a
test basis.
The seven Baby Bells are currently banned from the long-distance market
under the terms of the 1982 anti-trust court case which spun them off from
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph. Regulators feared they would use their
monopoly power in the local market to compete unfairly in the long-distance
arena.
However, technological factors and a pro-competition regulatory environment
are gradually whittling away at the local monopoly.
