<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 93 / International Company News: Top Canadian bank battered by
loan losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Royal Bank of Canada, the country's biggest financial institution, has had
another disappointing year, with earnings hit by restructuring charges and
unexpectedly high loan losses, especially in real estate.
Net earnings totalled CDollars 300m (USDollars 225.7m), or 46 cents a share,
in the year to October 31, compared with CDollars 107m, or a loss of five
cents a share, in 1992. Return on equity was a meagre 2.4 per cent,
following last year's negative return of 0.3 per cent.
The previously-announced charges, totalling CDollars 410m, reflect the costs
of integrating the operations of Royal Trust, which the bank acquired
earlier this year, and an internal restructuring plan. RBC is cutting 4,100
jobs from its payroll, equal to almost 8 per cent of its workforce.
After the charges, the bank posted a CDollars 420m fourth-quarter loss,
equal to CDollars 1.47 a share, against a loss of CDollars 473m, or CDollars
1.63, a year earlier.
Loan-loss provisions for the year were CDollars 1.75bn.
This is lower than the CDollars 2.05bn set aside in 1992, when the bank was
hit by its exposure to Olympia &amp; York, the failed real estate developer.
The final 1993 provisions, however, are more than double the CDollars 820m
estimated at the end of the first quarter. Provisions for sour commercial
real-estate loans have now reached 20 per cent of the bank's gross property
portfolio.
Ms Donna Toth, analyst at Nesbitt Thomson in Toronto, said RBC's problems
stemmed from aggressive lending policies with inadequate controls. Several
of the bank's most senior corporate credit officers have taken early
retirement in the past year.
On the brighter side, Mr Allan Taylor, chairman, said retail banking and
treasury operations performed strongly, while the bank's investment banking
subsidiary, RBC Dominion Securities, posted record earnings. Non-performing
loans have dropped to CDollars 3.26bn on October 31 from CDollars 3.48bn a
year earlier, with the level of non-performing consumer loans falling for
the first time in four years.
The inclusion of Royal Trust from September boosted assets by 19 per cent to
CDollars 164.9bn. Royal Trust's operations have been 'close to' break-even
since then.
</TEXT>
