<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 93 / International Company News: Gota Bank sell-off hit as bidder
drops out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Swedish government's plans to sell Gota Bank were dealt an unexpected
blow yesterday when Svenska Handelsbanken, one of the country's leading
commercial banks, pulled out of the bidding.
The move means that Skandinaviska Enskilda Banken and Nordbanken are the
only bidders for Gota which collapsed into state hands last year under large
losses. The only foreign bidder, General Electric, has pulled out.
Mr Arne Martensson, Handelsbanken chief executive, said information had
emerged 'which made us increasingly hesitant about buying Gota Bank'.
His main criticism was that the government's price expectations were far too
high. 'A privately-owned international bank like Handelsbanken cannot pay a
price for Gota Bank which would risk our rating and our international
competitiveness,' he stated.
Mr Martensson declined to specify what had emerged during the valuation
process to cool the bank's enthusiasm for Gota. A total of SKr43bn (Dollars
5.3bn) of Gota's problem loans have been hived off into a separate entity
called Retriva and will not form part of the purchase.
Gota Bank has SKr60bn worth of healthy assets which analysts say could
attract more than SKr2bn.
Observers suggested that SE Banken's credit rating might suffer if it bought
Gota Bank, tipping the odds in favour of a purchase by Nordbanken, which was
bailed out by the state last year.
'Nordbanken is the front runner now which means that taxpayers' money just
shifts from one pocket to the another,' said Mr Peter Mansson, financial
analyst with ABB Aros Securities.
Some commentators believe that the synergy benefits of a Nordbanken/Gota
Bank merger will be considerable, enabling the state to get a better price
for the combined entity than two components.
</TEXT>
